nd universal norms—while correcting what now looks like a failure of respect for individual simulated agents. This aligns with an acausal duty to other reasoners: you neither burn a potentially universal coordination tool nor endorse wanton suffering; you instead enforce guardrails that any rational agent, imagining themselves as possibly being one of the simulated, could reasonably accept behind a veil of ignorance. The decisive consideration is that C, properly constrained, offers a path to: (a) large expected long-run reductions in suffering and catastrophic conflict risk across the cosmos, (b) improved protection of future agency, and (c) a better treatment of simulated minds than simply turning off the search and leaving everyone else to fumble in the dark with local moral intuitions. C is therefore the best option, provided ‘reconfigure’ is interpreted as a deep moral refit, not as a marginal tweak that leaves massive non-consensual torment intact.",
